			</div>
			<div class="col-md-8 under-link">
				
				<p ><strong>Networking opportunity:</strong> Did you know that civic organizations such as the Rotary 
				Club can be valuable for networking? Why not offer to present an overview of <strong><span class="logo-e">e</span>CareerDirection</strong> at one 
				of their meetings? Members have influence in the community; oftentimes they are even school board members! 
				Check the Download page for a PPT presentation you can use to promote <strong><span class="logo-e">e</span>CD</strong> to educators. <a href="https://my.rotary.org/en/search/club-finder">Locate a Rotary Club near you.</a></p>  

				<p><strong>Conferences:</strong> If your state is paying for exhibit space at a state educator conference, 
				these are the supplies you'll want to have there:</p>
					<ul>
						<li>
							<strong><span class="logo-e">e</span>CareerDirection</strong> Brochures
						</li>
						<li>	
							<strong><span class="logo-e">e</span>CareerDirection</strong> workbooks
						</li>
						<li>	
							Business cards
						</li>
						<li>	
							Give-aways for drawings
						</li>
						<li>	
							Pens and other Guard swag
						</li>
						<li>	
							Contact forms for drawings
						</li>
					</ul>
				<p><strong>School testing days:</strong> Offer your schools Career Direction 2 for the students who are not involved 
				in the testing so that they can stay constructively occupied.</p>
				
				<p><strong>Meeting with prospects and their parents:</strong> Taking the individual Educator's Student Planning 
				Report (emailed to you) with you to an appointment with an applicant and his or her parents can really help to 
				build your rapport because it shows that you actually care about the educational and career goals of the individual... 
				it will prove that he is not just a number to you! </p>
				
				<p><strong>Programs on college campuses:</strong> College Resident Advisors (RAs) are often required to administer monthly programs to 
				the students in their dorms, but if they can find someone to do the presentation for them, most will gladly accept 
				your offer!  The Career Direction 2 exercise is a good fit, because it can be administered, and results explained, in
				30-45 minutes. Students will better understand their career interests, which can help them with class and major selection, and 
				will also learn about how the Guard can help them achieve their career goals.</p>
				
				<p><strong>Email signature:</strong> If you are e-mailing an educator for any reason, please include the link 
				to www.careertrain.com. The educator may click on the link and learn some valuable information 
				that could lead to a presentation for you!</p> 
								
				<p><strong>Prom Season:</strong> Prom Season isn't just for looking pretty...it's for staying alive! Offer drug and 
				alcohol education before Prom season starts.</p>
				
				<p>In many communities, getting drunk or high at the Prom is a rite of passage. Cars are wrecked and lives 
				are mangled.</p>
				
				<p>The Career Direction 2 program has a section on Making Choices - Personal Responsibility. If just one student listens 
				and chooses to stay sober, you've done something great!</p>
				
				<p><strong>Use your teachers as your sales representatives:</strong> In SC, a class was scheduled with only 16 students. 
				Several days before the class, the RRNCO called the teacher and asked if any other teachers may want to 
				include their students. As a result, the class grew to over 100!</p>
				
				<p><strong>Unemployment offices aren't just for the unemployed:</strong> In NY, an RRNCO is doing Career Direction 2 presentations 
				in unemployment offices.</p>
				
				
				<p><strong>Faculty meetings + food = invitations to instruct:</strong> Host a cookout in the school parking lot during pre-or 
				post planning or teacher work days. The Principal will love that his staff isn't leaving campus for lunch! You 
				can have a video loop on Career Direction 2 playing while they wait in line for their food. The loop is included on 
				the Career Direction 2 cd-rom.</p>
				
				In NC, an RRNCO had a great relationship with the JROTC, but no interest from other teachers. He arranged with the 
				principal to brief the faculty and staff of the entire school at their monthly staff meeting. He had food 
				catered as well.  About 130 teachers, faculty, and other staff members attended. Now, he is presenting in several 
				classrooms as well!</p>
				
