				<p><strong>Here are some ideas for summer activities:</strong></p>
				
				<ol>
					<li>
						Present Career Direction 2 at:
					</li>
						<ul>
							<li>
								summer schools
							</li>
							<li>
								summer camps
							</li>
							<li>
								Unemployment offices
							</li>
							<li>
								GED classes
							</li>
							<li>
								alternative learning centers
							</li>
							<li>
								YMCAs
							</li>
							<li>
								colleges and tech schools
							</li>
							<li>
								Some schools have 12-month schedules. This Web site is a good resource for identifying 
								them: <a href="http://nayre.org/schools.html" target="blank">nayre.org</a>
							</li>
						</ul>
					<li>
						Invite educators to "A Day in the Guard" at one of your training facilities where you 
						can tell them about school programs and the training and benefits available to students through the Guard.
					</li>
					<li>
						Provide a summer camp for JROTC detachments.
					</li>
					<li>
						School Administrators work during the summer. In fact, this is when they plan the school calendar. 
						Make an appointment to meet them and learn about their needs and figure out how you can help.
					</li>
					
					<li>
						Bring your calendar to the school and ask what dates the teachers need help with their 
						classes and offer to present Career Direction 2 or another Guard SEV.
					</li>
				</ol>
				
				<p><b>Follow-up is key to booking future presentations:</b> Get a bunch of giveaways and go by your schools to say thanks 
				for supporting the Guard this year. While you are there take the list of presentations conducted this school year 
				and schedule for next school year.</p>
				
				
				<p>You can start out by saying something like, "Last fall, you had us present Career Direction 2 to your ____________ 
				class during the third week of October. Did that time-frame work well for you? I want to lock it in on my calendar so I can make sure I am available for your class again."</p>
				
				<p><b>Saying thank you isn't just good manners:</b> The busier you get, the more important this little detail becomes. 
				Follow up every meeting with an email thank you message IMMEDIATELY. Why? The follow-up message:</p>
					<ul>
						<li>
							Summarizes your conversation
						</li>
						<li>
							Re-emphasizes agreement that has already been made
						</li>
						<li>
							States what next steps are needed and who is doing what
						</li>
						<li>
							Opens the door for further communication
						</li>
						<li>
							Introduces new information
						</li>
					</ul>
				
				<p>An easy way to accomplish this is to create standard follow-up emails depending on different scenarios. As you finish 
				a phone call with an educator, email them right then. At the end of each day, email EVERY EDUCATOR YOU VISITED THAT DAY. 
				It isn't just good manners, it is good business.</p><br />
				
